data.content:
MSTest has a dedicated `CollectionAssert` class plus better assertion methods. Your current approach using `Assert.IsTrue` everywhere gives poor failure messages (just "expected true, got false").

Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Clear count assertion with useful failure message
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Verify all users are active
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Check a specific element exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

- **`Assert.AreEqual(expected, actual)`** — shows both values on failure instead of just "false"
- **`CollectionAssert`** — purpose-built for collections:
  - `CollectionAssert.AllSatisfy(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive))` (.NET 8+)
  - `CollectionAssert.Contains(list, item)`
  - `CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual)` — order-sensitive
  - `CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — order-insensitive
- **Add message parameters** — gives context when `Assert.IsTrue` is unavoidable
- **`Assert.IsNotNull`** over `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` — clearer intent

If you're on **.NET 8+ with MSTest 3.x**, you also get `Assert.That.Sequence()` for fluent collection assertions.
